    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe quickfix list is a very useful builtin feature, especially for showing diagnostics in your workspace / buffer. It however lacks auto-updating of these diagnostics. This is something that new users coming from an IDE (like vscode) might expect, as these IDEs often also have a window with diagnostics below the buffers. It makes the overall experience with using diagnostics in the qflist much better and gives working with diagnostics a more modern feel.\n\nImplementing the qflist as diagnostic handler is fairly trivial thanks to `vim.diagnostic.handler`. However, users might not think to implement this themself. It would be great for discoverability to have this as builtin handler, even when it's turned off as default.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI currently use this in my own config:\n\n```lua\nvim.diagnostic.handlers[\"quickfix\"] = {\n  show = function(_, _, _, _)\n    vim.diagnostic.setqflist({ open = false })\n  end,\n\n  hide = function(_, _)\n    vim.fn.setqflist({}, 'r')\n  end\n}\n```\n\nand that works already quite well.\n\nThis solves the problem by creating a diagnostic handler that just sets the qflist with available diagnostics. I think the show function is called on DiagnosticChanged, thus this would update the qflist when the list of diagnostics changes. The cost is minimal, and provides a modern experience for working with diagnostics.",
